I've been watching some of GM games and am less afraid of moves like this now. I didn't want to trade off my Bishop with something like 15. Rfd1 Nxd3 16. Rxd3. This keeps my Bishop on the potential dangerous b1-h7 diagonal but also makes the a2-g8 diagonal an option down the road.
Again playing actively hoping to double my pawns and weaken my Kingside structure
But, my Knight has a very nice square and now I'm attacking both the Bishop and the dangling a-pawn

This move is probably the worst choice as it does not deal with either of the threats. The only safe square for the Bishop is e8 and my opponent likely did not want to disconnect his rooks but this doubles his pawns and loses a pawn as well. Probably better was either 16. ... Be8 or 16. ... a6
